 religious identities of Southeast Asia were largely formed by the experiences of the fifteenth through seventeenth centuries, when international commerce boomed before eventually falling under the domination of well-armed European powers intent on monopoly. This book is the first to document the full range of responses to the profound changes of this period: urbanization and the burgeoning of commerce; the proliferation of firearms; an increase in the number and strength of states; and the shift from experimental spirit worship to the universalist scriptural religions of Islam, Christianity, and Theravada Buddhism. Bringing together ten essays by an international group of historians, Southeast Asia in the Early Modern Era shows how various states adapted to new pressures and compares economic, religious, and political developments among the major cultures of the area.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aAndaya, Barbara Watson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndaya, Leonard Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshii, Yoneo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKathirithamby-Wells, Jeyamalar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLieberman, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManguin, Pierre-Yves, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Anthony J. S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReid, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReis Thomaz, Luis Filipe Ferreira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Keith W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l